  "number": 2129,
  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/2129",
  "title": "Search multiple indices with combined results in one hits area",
  "body": "Through Algolia's API I can see that [it is possible to query multiple indices](https://www.algolia.com/doc/api-client/javascript/search/#search-multiple-indices).\r\nBut is it possible to have two sets of results ranked against each other?\r\n\r\nThe main use case is, you have two indexes of data with different properties, but you want to give the user the ability to see results from both **and ranked against each other** (this is key). \r\n\r\nYou could add multiple indexes when configuring instant search:\r\n```\r\ninstantsearch({\r\n  appId: config.appId,\r\n  apiKey: config.apiKey,\r\n  indexNames: ['index1','index2'] \r\n});\r\n```\r\nNow each query would apply a search to both, and return a combined result that ranks them against each other.\r\n\r\nI'm sure there are complications in being able to rank two different structures against each other, but often you have very different data sets and want to embed along with them some other kind of data.\r\n\r\nOne example would be, you have an index of web pages, and you have an index of company locations.\r\nYou want a user to be able to search the web pages for specific content, but if their search matches company locations, you want to highlight those in order of relevance to other web page results to the user.\r\n\r\nCould something like this be done by creating a custom instantsearch widget where you manually combined two sets of results in some fashion?",
